communicated by:
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>

[The total number of confirmed cases in the USA and territories is now 3 770 012 including 142 064 deaths, an increase from 3 695 025 cases and 141 118 deaths in the past 24 hours. New York City had a cumulative total of 217 562 cases as of 13:00 EDT (GMT-4) on 17 Jul 2020 (+332 since 16 Jul 2020) including 18 758 (+4 since 16 Jul 2020) confirmed deaths and an additional 4619 probable deaths (https://www1.nyc.gov/site/doh/covid/covid-19-data.page).

The top 10 states in terms of daily reported cases in descending order are Florida, California, Texas, Arizona, Georgia, Tennessee, Louisiana, North Carolina, Alabama, and South Carolina -- the same 10 states as yesterday (16 Jul 2020), slightly rearranged. Note that 6 of the 10 states are located in the south east region of the country. This list includes states that are showing major increases in daily cases reported beginning with the lifting of restrictions around the end of May 2020. All of the top 10 states reported more than 1000 newly confirmed cases in the past 24 hours, with the range being 1977 to 11 466. In terms of cumulative case reports, the order is unchanged from previous days with New York as number one, followed by California, Florida, Texas, New Jersey, Illinois, Arizona, Georgia, Massachusetts, and Pennsylvania. A total of 45 states and entities now have reported more than 10 000 cumulative cases each.

In the past 24 hours, the proportion increase of newly confirmed cases was 2.0%. The 7-day average of newly confirmed cases for the past 7 days is 19.2% higher than the 7-day average for the preceding 7 days, consistent with the ongoing pandemic in the country but gradually slowing down, but may reflect a change in reporting in the USA that began on Monday 13 Jul 2020.

The Centers for Disease Control and Prevention website (https://www.cdc.gov/coronavirus/2019-ncov/covid-data/covidview/index.html) has data on cases, hospitalization, testing, and epidemiologic variables such as age, race, ILI (influenza-like illness), surveillance, and emergency room visits, which are definitely worth reviewing, as a welcome series of analyses. According to the CDC data, as of 17 Jul 2020, the percentage of laboratory specimens testing positive for SARS-CoV-2 with a molecular assay remains at 9% out of 47 313 367 tests performed, consistent with the ongoing, not-yet-under-control pandemic in the country (https://www.cdc.gov/coronavirus/2019-ncov/cases-updates/testing-in-us.html).

A map of the United States can be seen at http://www.mapsofworld.com/usa/ and a HealthMap/ProMED map at https://promedmail.org/promed-post?place=7587301,106. - Mod.MPP]

