communicated by:
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>

[According to the data on the Worldometer website, the total number of reported cases of COVID-19 worldwide is now 14 189 018, with reports of cases by 217 countries and territories worldwide. As predicted yesterday (16 Jul 2020) the reported cumulative case count did pass 14 million cases, taking 5 days since it crossed the 13 million case mark. The global case count rose by 1.7% in the past 24 hours. The USA and Brazil are still the most severely affected countries in terms of cumulative case counts, although India crossed the 1 million case mark yesterday (16 Jul 2020). In the past 24 hours, the USA reported the most newly confirmed cases (74 987) followed by India (34 820) and Brazil (33 959). The total cumulative case counts for the top 5 countries (USA, Brazil, India, Russia, and Peru) represent over half of the total cases reported globally (56.1%). A global total of 599 339 deaths have been reported, an increase of 6666 deaths in the past 24 hours.

In descending rank order, the USA is number 1 for the number of newly confirmed cases in the past 24 hours, followed by India, Brazil, South Africa, Colombia, Mexico, Russia, Argentina, Peru, and Bangladesh. These 10 countries are the same as 2 days ago, just slight variances in order (15 Jul 2020). All these countries are currently experiencing major community-based transmission and considered global hot spots. The range in the top 10 daily newly confirmed cases goes from 3034 to 74 987. The number of daily newly confirmed cases is climbing rapidly in the USA. Also worthy of note is that 6 of the top 10 countries for daily reported newly confirmed cases are from the Americas region, consistent with the continued dominance of SARS-CoV-2 activity in this region.

Comparing the 7-day averages of daily confirmed cases from the past 7 days and those from 8-14 days ago, there is an increase of 9.0%, again consistent with the ongoing pandemic but slowing down in terms of daily growth.

Impression: The SARS-CoV-2 is still actively being transmitted in all regions of the world, and many countries are showing increases in their daily newly confirmed case counts. That being said, the most severely affected region is the Americas with cases increasing on a daily basis, even though the comparative 7-day average suggests things may be slowing down (or reporting is slowing down). - Mod.MPP]
